<b>Norman Bird</b> (<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../436/22436.xml">
30 October</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../676/34676.xml">
1920</link> â€“ <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../710/1710.xml">
22 April</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../984/35984.xml">
2005</link>) was one of Britain's foremost character actors. Often sporting a moustache and an air of worried resignation, he seemed to specialise in downtrodden roles. Describing himself as "the man with the cardigan", his doleful looks ensured that he was usually cast as henpecked husbands, petty officials or interfering busybodies.<p>

Bird was born in <site wordnetid="108651247" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../811/351811.xml">
Coalville</link></site>
, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../153/61153.xml">
Leicestershire</link>, <country wordnetid="108544813" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../316/9316.xml">
England</link></country>
. A <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../026/163026.xml">
RADA</link> graduate, he made his West End debut in <actor wordnetid="109765278" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<director wordnetid="110014939" confidence="0.9173553029164789">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../191/215191.xml">
Peter Brook</link></director>
</actor>
's production of <it><comedy wordnetid="107015510" confidence="0.8">
<writing_style wordnetid="107092158" confidence="0.8">
<dramatic_composition wordnetid="107007684" confidence="0.8">
<play wordnetid="107007945" confidence="0.8">
<written_communication wordnetid="106349220" confidence="0.8">
<writing wordnetid="106362953" confidence="0.8">
<drama wordnetid="106376154" confidence="0.8">
<expressive_style wordnetid="107066659" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../378/85378.xml">
The Winter's Tale</link></expressive_style>
</drama>
</writing>
</written_communication>
</play>
</dramatic_composition>
</writing_style>
</comedy>
</it> at the Phoenix Theatre in 1951. His first film appearance was as the foreman in <it><play wordnetid="107007945" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../888/58888.xml">
An Inspector Calls</link></play>
</it> (1954).</p>
<p>

He was a familiar face to British cinema audiences of the 60s, appearing in such classic films as <it><movie wordnetid="106613686" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../993/203993.xml">
The League of Gentlemen</link></movie>
</it> (1960), <it><movie wordnetid="106613686" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../182/3375182.xml">
The Angry Silence</link></movie>
</it> (1961), <it><movie wordnetid="106613686" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../501/8427501.xml">
Whistle Down the Wind</link></movie>
</it> (1961) and <it><movie wordnetid="106613686" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../186/166186.xml">
Victim</link></movie>
</it> (1961).</p>
<p>

He went on to make nearly 70 films and over 200 television appearances, notably as Mr Braithwaite in <it><series wordnetid="108457976" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../515/241515.xml">
Worzel Gummidge</link></series>
</it> (1979-81) and as Mr Arrad in the <it><series wordnetid="108457976" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../673/11673.xml">
Fawlty Towers</link></series>
</it> episode "<episode wordnetid="106396330" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../586/5904586.xml">
Waldorf Salad</link></episode>
" (1979). His long list of credits include <it><link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../880/175880.xml">
Steptoe and Son</link></it>, <it><series wordnetid="108457976" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
